                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> I agree with Tenaiya.<br /><br />In EQ, you get what you PLAY for, not what you pay for.  Do you (those whining about drops) play 50-100 hrs/week?  If not, then you probably ain't Uber and you probalby weren't in Tier 2 zones the first week to take advantage of the higher drop rates.  Maybe you were level 60 but weren't spending time in PoP but instead doing stuff in other zones.  Who's choice was that?  The drop rate nerf was just another nerf.  Get over it.<br /><br />The one thing I haven't yet seen posted is the possiblity that VI is smarter than most folks ... and that maybe, just maybe, they planned to have a higher drop rate of Parchments/Runes in the Tier 2+ planes for a week or so.  Why?  Because maybe they WANTED to entice the Uberguidls into Tier 3 zones and AWAY from the Tier 1 & 2 content that the lower-level guilds would be interested in trying.<br /><br />When guilds of different levels start bumping into each other, it's bad for business at SOE.  <br /><br />For each conflict, a GM spends a couple hours dealing with sorting out who got there first, deciding who gets a shot at the mob, and then "appeasing" the 60 customers in the losing guild by respawning nameds after the uberguild is done, telling the losers tough luck try again in a week, or whatever else it is that GMs do in these cases.  Multiply this times 50 servers and you've got a LOT of GMs spending a LOT of time settling disputes for 7000 customers instead of fixing the other 393,000 *OTHER* customers' stuck_player or poofed_gear_during_mid-CR_servercrash or scammer or broken_quest_lost_item or random_stupidity problems.  So 1 1/2 percent of the population ends up with 90% of the support resources... <br /><br />Since (from the Business2.com article) there's only an average of one GM per shift per server (for 24x7 coverage), which would you have them doing?  Catering to the 2% of uber and tier 2 guilds or the rest of us in the other 98% of the customer base?  In fact, the uberguilds get very little attention compared to the value they give to SOE and the rest of the playerbase -- they're the real testers of high end EQ content, since they get to see it all first and deal with all the mob/quest/loot bugs.<br /><br />It makes complete sense to me and I bet the server GMs are quite happy that there's plenty more high end content keeping ALL the raiding guilds busy and away from each other.<br /><br />And in fact, I think that most ubervolken will agree that SOE did a better job on managing the gameplay rollout of PoP content (i.e. character flags) than they did with Luclin (random-drop quest timesinks for Seru/VT keys).  <br /><br />Or maybe it was just a marketing gimmick to make more customers go out and purchase PoP instead of waiting until they got to level 60.<br /><br />I only play 10-20 hrs/week.  Why should I get what I don't deserve?  Hell, I'm be happy just being part of a multi-guild raid wiping on Trakanon or killing Hate/Fear/Air/Chardok minibosses for my epic pieces.<br /><br />Folks seem to be having a hard time accepting that PoP was designed to separate the ubers from the masses.  <br /><br />The way things seem to have progressed from a game design concept (please correct me if I get this wrong) is as follows.<br /><br />In Antonica: <br />Spells = Bought<br />Items = Dropped or Quested<br />Access to High Level Content = no restrictions.<br />Factions = mostly for role-playing.<br /><br />The amount and variety of High Level Content was basically nil.  Once you hit level 50 you had 2 Dragons and Guk and what else?.<br /><br />Kunark: <br />Spells = Dropped (some Quested)<br />Items = Dropped or Quested<br />Access to High Level Content = via keys from mob Kill quests.<br />Factions = All Hail the faction-based quest!<br /><br />The Amount and variety of High Level Content was SO much greater it balanced the MUCH greater amount of time to get to level 60.  Here we got a big separation between the 50 and the 60s.  Kunark was designed to spread out the player base, and it worked.<br /><br /><br />Velious: <br />Spells = Bought<br />Items = Quested or dropped<br />Access to High Level Content = via faction + keys from faction driven kill quests.  <br />Factions = this expansion is all about factions.<br /><br />Again, there was lots of stuff for the level 55-60 crowd to do, which was good because the percentage of players in that level range was growing rapidly.<br /><br />Luclin: <br />Spells = Bought (Uber spells Dropped)<br />Items = Dropped (most mid/low level quest items sucked)<br />Access to Content = via random mob drop timesinks.<br />Factions = Factions matter exactly how in Luclin?  <br /><br />Goofy-high mob AC and immunities were a twist, but more of an annoyance which resulted in greater timesinks to get bane weapons or whatever it is they had to do.  Pretty much everyone at level 60 hated Luclin due to the timesink factor.  And only the Uberguilds had the resources to get to the highest level content, leaving the other guilds to bump into each other in non-Luclin zones.  Ancient spells were limited to just the 1 or 2 top mobs, which pissed people off, but folks got over it since they're supposed to be hard to get (again separating the ubers from the rest).  Meanwhile, the percentage of the player population at level 60 skyrocketed.<br /><br />So now we have PoP:<br />Spells = Dropped<br />Items = Dropped  (low/mid level quest items are better than Luclin at least)<br />Access to Content = via kills.  <br />Factions = Besides PoK quests, are there any factions that matter?<br /><br />The Uberguilds go on a tear (since their Luclin gear could handle the higher DPS from the mobs), and the rest of the folks were stuck grinding in Tier 1.  This is good.  It leaves more content for the rest of us gimps.  The only real bitch so far about PoP is the spell drop rate for the 60+ folks who didn't have PoP (or weren't playing there) the first few weeks.  <br /><br />Getting back to the relevance of all this to Daedrea's original post about drop rates and taking 2+ years to get all your spells... <br /><br />Wasn't there a simliar problem in Kunark at first with the hundreds of new spells dropping only from certain mobs in certain zones?  And how long did it take everyone to get their spells to the point where they were generally satisfied?  I for one was able to buy all of my 50-60 spells over the last few months (except for Demi, EoT) for an average of about 75pp each.<br /><br />VI has stated that they watch the drop rates of key game-balancing items/spells/exp quite carefully, and that they make adjustments to content accordingly (somtimes nerfing, but also increasing... e.g. Eye of Innoruk, cleric epic spawn, etc.).  Sure they've adjusted spell drop rates quite severely to make up for the initial gold rush.  But I bet they'll increase the drop rates and loot tables just like they've done before as the bulk of players move into the 60+ level range.  That way the economy for spell drops won't crash or explode.  The best thing about the parchment/rune concept is that we won't be seeing outrageous prices for any of the spells, since they're all on the same loot table... and this is a very good thing, IMO.<br /><br />And speaking of the 61+ spell economy ... on Nameless, you can buy all your 61-62 PoP spells for about 2k each in the bazaar, and the price has dropped from 20k to 5k to 2k since release.  And just last night someone was auctioning a 62 Wiz spell for 1k.  If you can make 2k in 2-3 hours of plat farming, why bother grinding 5-10 hours with a group only to lose the roll?  I'll stick with /bazaar and watch the prices come down.<br /><br />Seems to me the drop rate ain't all that bad if prices settle to about 1k per spell (which seems to be where they're heading).  <br /><br />But then again... i'm just a newb.  <img src="images/eyebrows_125.gif" border="0" alt="" title="" align="middle" /><br /><br /><br /><br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=310159" target="_blank">Gunkk</a><br />56 Iksar Necro<br />The Nameless<br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
