                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Nah VI has never needed to add in temporary content (ie more xp and high drop rates) to entice ubers into certain zones/areas. By their nature, ubers will go through all content in under-par zones fairly quickly and look for the biggest things to kill. The problem is that whoever is responsible for drop rates and such doesn't seem capable of understanding the concept of testing prior to release. The other associated problem is with the people in charge of controlling the flow of items into the game tend to over-react and nerf things into oblivion. What they don't seem to realise is that overnerfing doesn't compensate for the number of whatever items have already entered the game. The numbers might work out to compensate for the initial flood of items, but in practice compensation doesn't occur. Instead, there ends up being a selective division between players that ends up getting bigger and bigger.<br /><br />The previous times this occured it never really affected large numbers of players directly as only certain zones/areas were affected and changes were typically limited to reduction of xp (*shrug* always other places to xp) and reduction in drop frequency of certain items which were usable only by certain classes. This time however, the nerfage affected every single class that can cast spells on every single server. It doesn't take a math genius to work out that there are more players that are capable of casting spells than there are players who can't. Therefore the much larger, and justified, outcry over the current situation.<br /><br />There isn't that much of a problem with the 61-62 spells. Spectrals are dropping at relatively reasonable rates compared to level 60 spells. At the very least, one doesn't have to kill a dragon to get a level 56 spell.<br /><br />The problem is more in the 63+ spell area. Until a patch changes things, the people who need as many of the new spells as possible, ie the non-uber crowd, simply aren't going to get them anytime soon. The problem is partly due to the low drop rates but it is also greatly affected by the method of obtaining the spells.<br />The parchment turn-in idea was good in theory but exceedingly shoddy and frustrating in practice. It works (grudgingly) acceptably with the 61-62 spells because there are a lot of people of those levels and the parchment drop rate is reasonable. However, when you get to the 63+ spells, only a small proportion of the caster population is able to get hold of these parchments. VI expects these spells to trickle down. <br /><br />But, trickle down only happens if there is an excess. At the rate that ethereals are currently dropping, they will always end up where they are most needed. First they will go to classes that are seen as being more important to guild development, then they will go to the classes with the largest numbers of people missing spells (this will happen even if they are handed out at random, the class with the largest proportion of people without spells will have a larger representation). Necros are neither seen as a particularly important class nor is there an abundance of them. Trickle down of necro spells simply won't happen particularly quickly because the high end necro population is low. The same can be said of any class that is marginally represented in the high end game. <br /><br />Many people turning in parchment for a class = many excess spells = lots of trickle down<br /><br />Few people turning in parchment for a class = few excess spells = slow trickle down<br /><br />Essentially, once the high end necros get all their 63+ spells, they'll never have to turn in another parchment again. This pretty much shuts off the tap for those necros who won't have a chance to get to Tier 3 zones. They'll have to wait for new raid-oriented necros to march up through the ranks before they get another chance at those spells. Trickle down never worked and it sure as hell won't work if the tap gets shut off all the time.<br /><br /><br />Tenaiya Soulscorcher</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
